      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "But x is evaluated twice (one for condition and one for assignation). When using null coalescing operator <code>int y = x ?? -1</code>, x is evaluated once."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 935202,
        "reputation" : 50314,
        "user_id" : 964243,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 66,
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/fL1rH.png?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Boann",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/964243/boann"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1729434878,
      "post_id" : 5223065,
      "comment_id" : 139488892,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "Careful! It&#39;s still possible for <code>int y = (x != null) ? x : -1;</code> to throw a <code>NullPointerException</code>, if <code>x</code> is a field changed by another thread during evaluation of the expression. This can be avoided only by pulling <code>x</code> into a local variable. The real null coalescing operator doesn&#39;t have this weakness."
    } ],
